}```

It returns the last matching element in a sequence of comments and single-newline whitespaces. So if there are consecutive comments, the method would traverse through all of them and return the first one (the one closest to the previous declaration).

So I can check if there are consecutive comments by looking at what comes AFTER the returned element. If the returned element is a comment, and there's another comment after it (separated only by single-newline whitespace), then there are consecutive comments!


I'll craft a targeted implementation to detect these consecutive comment scenarios. By examining the previous leaf and its subsequent elements, I can precisely identify when multiple comments appear in sequence. This approach leverages the existing method's behavior to efficiently detect comment clusters.

